{{Infobox fluorine}}
'''Fluorine''' is a [[chemical element]] with the symbol '''F''' and [[atomic number]] 9. It is the lightest [[halogen]] and exists as a highly toxic pale yellow [[diatomic molecule|diatomic]] gas at [[standard conditions for temperature and pressure|standard conditions]]. As the most [[electronegativity|electronegative]] element, it is extremely reactive: almost all other elements, including some noble gases, form compounds with fluorine.

Among the elements, fluorine ranks [[Abundance of the chemical elements|24th in universal abundance and 13th in terrestrial abundance]]. [[Fluorite]], the primary mineral source of fluorine, was first described in 1529; as it was added to metal ores to lower their melting points for [[smelting]], the Latin verb ''{{lang|la|fluo}}'' meaning "flow" became associated with it. Proposed as an element in 1810, fluorine proved difficult and dangerous to separate from its compounds, and several early experimenters died or sustained injuries from their attempts. Only in 1886 did French chemist [[Henri Moissan]] isolate elemental fluorine using low-temperature [[electrolysis]], a process still employed for modern production. Industrial synthesis of fluorine gas for [[uranium enrichment]], its largest application, began during the [[Manhattan Project]] in World War II. 

Due to the expense of refining pure fluorine, most commercial applications of the element involve the use of its compounds, with about half of mined fluorite used in [[steelmaking]]. The rest is converted into corrosive [[hydrogen fluoride]] en route to various organic fluorides, or into [[cryolite]] which plays a key role in [[Hall<U+2013>H<U+00E9>roult process|aluminium refining]]. Organic fluorides have very high chemical and thermal stability; their major uses are as [[refrigerant]]s, electrical insulation and cookware, the last as [[polytetrafluoroethylene|PTFE]] (Teflon). Pharmaceuticals such as [[atorvastatin]] and [[fluoxetine]] also contain fluorine, and the [[fluoride|fluoride ion]] inhibits dental cavities, and so finds use in toothpaste and [[water fluoridation]]. [[fluorochemical industry|Global fluorochemical]] sales amount to over [[United States dollar|US$]]15 billion a year.

[[Fluorocarbon]] gases are generally [[greenhouse gas]]es with [[global-warming potential]]s 100 to 20,000 times that of carbon dioxide. [[Organofluorine compound]]s, with an uncertain potential impact on health, persist in the environment due to the strength of the [[carbon<U+2013>fluorine bond]]. Fluorine has no known metabolic role in mammals; a few plants synthesize organofluorine poisons to deter herbivores.
{{TOC limit|limit=3}}

==Characteristics==

===Electron configuration===
[[File:Fluorine shielding.svg|alt=Two concentric rings showing valence and non-valence electron shells|Simplified structure of the fluorine atom|left|thumb]]
Fluorine atoms have nine electrons, one fewer than [[neon]], and [[electron configuration]] 1s<sup>2</sup>2s<sup>2</sup>2p<sup>5</sup>: two electrons in a filled inner shell and seven in an outer shell requiring one more to be filled. The outer electrons are ineffective at nuclear [[Shielding effect|shielding]], and experience a high [[effective nuclear charge]] of 9 <U+2212> 2 = '''7'''; this affects the atom's physical properties.{{sfn|Jaccaud et al.|2000|p=381}}

Fluorine's [[ionization energy|first ionization energy]] is third-highest among all elements, behind helium and neon,{{sfn|Dean|1999|p=564}} which complicates the removal of electrons from neutral fluorine atoms. It also has a high [[electron affinity]], second only to [[chlorine]],{{sfn|Lide|2004|pp=10.137<U+2013>10.138}} and tends to capture an electron to become [[isoelectronicity|isoelectronic]] with the noble gas neon;{{sfn|Jaccaud et al.|2000|p=381}} it has the highest [[electronegativity]] of any element.<ref>{{harvnb|Moore|Stanitski|Jurs|2010|p=[https://books.google.com/?id=ZOm8L9oCwLMC&pg=PA156 156]}}.</ref> Fluorine atoms have a small [[Covalent radius of fluorine|covalent radius]] of around 60&nbsp;[[picometer]]s, similar to those of its [[period 2 element|period]] neighbors oxygen and neon.<ref name="CSD">{{Harvnb|Cordero et al.|2008}}.</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Pyykk<U+00F6>|Atsumi|2009}}.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Sources disagree on the radii of oxygen, fluorine, and neon atoms. Precise comparison is thus impossible.||group="note"}}
{{clear left}}

===Reactivity===
{{Main|Compounds of fluorine#Chemical characteristics of fluorine|l1=Chemical characteristics of fluorine}}
The [[bond energy]] of [[Compounds of fluorine#Difluorine|difluorine]] is much lower than that of either {{chem|Cl|2}} or {{chem|Br|2}} and similar to the easily cleaved [[peroxide]] bond; this, along with high electronegativity, accounts for fluorine's easy dissociation, high reactivity and strong bonds to non-fluorine atoms.{{sfn|Greenwood|Earnshaw|1998|p=804}}<ref>{{harvnb|Macomber|1996|p=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HyuogOtzoaYC&pg=PA230 230]}}</ref> Conversely, bonds to other atoms are very strong because of fluorine's high electronegativity. Unreactive substances like powdered steel, glass fragments, and [[asbestos]] fibers react quickly with cold fluorine gas; wood and water spontaneously combust under a fluorine jet.{{sfn|Jaccaud et al.|2000|p=382}}<ref name="pop mechanics F reactivity">{{harvnb|Nelson|1947}}.</ref>
{{external media|width=240px|float=left|video1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vtWp45Eewtw Bright flames] during fluorine reactions|video2 = Fluorine [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TLOFaWdPxB0 reacting with caesium]}}
Reactions of elemental fluorine with metals require varying conditions. [[Alkali metal]]s cause explosions and [[alkaline earth metal]]s display vigorous activity in bulk; to prevent [[Passivation (chemistry)|passivation]] from the formation of metal fluoride layers most other metals such as aluminium and iron must be powdered,{{sfn|Greenwood|Earnshaw|1998|p=804}} and [[noble metal]]s require pure fluorine gas at 300<U+2013>450&nbsp;<U+00B0>C (575<U+2013>850&nbsp;<U+00B0>F).{{sfn|Lidin|Molochko|Andreeva|2000|pp=442<U+2013>455}} Some solid nonmetals (sulfur, phosphorus) react vigorously in liquid air temperature fluorine.{{sfn|Wiberg|Wiberg|Holleman|2001|p=404}} [[Hydrogen sulfide]]{{sfn|Wiberg|Wiberg|Holleman|2001|p=404}} and [[sulfur dioxide]]{{sfn|Patnaik|2007|p=472}} combine readily with fluorine, the latter sometimes explosively; [[sulfuric acid]] exhibits much less activity, requiring elevated temperatures.{{sfn|Aigueperse et al.|2000|p=400}}

[[Hydrogen]], like the alkali metals, reacts explosively with fluorine.{{sfn|Greenwood|Earnshaw|1998|p=844}} [[Carbon]], as [[lamp black]], reacts at room temperature to yield [[fluoromethane]]. Graphite combines with fluorine above 400&nbsp;<U+00B0>C (750&nbsp;<U+00B0>F) to produce [[non-stoichiometric compound|non-stoichiometric]] [[carbon monofluoride]]; higher temperatures generate gaseous [[fluorocarbon]]s, sometimes with explosions.<ref name="Kuriakose, A. K.">{{harvnb|Kuriakose|Margrave|1965}}.</ref> Carbon dioxide and carbon monoxide react at or just above room temperature,<ref name="Hasegawa, Yasuo">{{harvnb|Hasegawa et al.|2007}}.</ref> whereas [[paraffin wax|paraffins]] and other organic chemicals generate strong reactions:<ref>{{harvnb|Lagow|1970|pp=64<U+2013>78}}.</ref> even fully substituted [[haloalkane]]s such as [[carbon tetrachloride]], normally incombustible, may explode.<ref name="Navarrini, Walter">{{harvnb|Navarrini et al.|2012}}.</ref> Although [[nitrogen trifluoride]] is stable, nitrogen requires an [[Electric discharge in gases|electric discharge]] at elevated temperatures for reaction due to its very strong [[triple bond]];{{sfn|Lidin|Molochko|Andreeva|2000|p=252}} ammonia may react explosively.<ref name="Anhydrous ammonia MSDS">{{Harvnb|Tanner Industries|2011}}.</ref><ref name="Scott I. Morrow">{{harvnb|Morrow|Perry|Cohen|1959}}.</ref> Oxygen does not combine with fluorine under ambient conditions, but can be made to using electric discharge at low temperatures and pressures; the products tend to disintegrate into their constituent elements when heated.<ref name="Emel<U+00E9>us Sharpe 1974 111">{{harvnb|Emel<U+00E9>us|Sharpe|1974|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=qi0vujzNSz4C&pg=PA111 111]}}.</ref>{{sfn|Wiberg|Wiberg|Holleman|2001|p=457}}<ref>{{harvnb|Brantley|1949|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=Yo7r_1qJG2gC&pg=PA26-IA83 26]}}.</ref> Heavier halogens{{sfn|Jaccaud et al.|2000|p=383}} and [[radon]]<ref>{{harvnb|Pitzer|1975}}.</ref> react readily with fluorine; the lighter noble gases [[xenon]] and [[krypton]] require special conditions.<ref name="Khriachtchev et al. 2000">{{harvnb|Khriachtchev et al.|2000}}.</ref>
{{clear left}}

===Phases===
{{main|Phases of fluorine}}
[[File:Beta fluorine unit cell.svg|right|thumb|Crystal structure of <U+03B2>-fluorine. Spheres indicate {{chem|F|2}} molecules that may assume any angle. Other molecules are constrained to planes.|alt=Cube with spherical shapes on the corners and center and spinning molecules in planes in faces]]
At room temperature, fluorine is a gas of [[diatomic molecule]]s,{{sfn|Jaccaud et al.|2000|p=382}} pale yellow when pure (but sometimes described as yellow-green).<ref>{{harvnb|Burdon|Emson|Edwards|1987}}.</ref> It has a characteristic pungent odor detectable at 20&nbsp;[[parts per billion|ppb]].{{sfn|Lide|2004|p=4.12}} Fluorine condenses into a bright yellow liquid at <U+2212>188&nbsp;<U+00B0>C (<U+2212>306&nbsp;<U+00B0>F), a similar transition temperature to those of oxygen and nitrogen.{{sfn|Dean|1999|p=523}}

Fluorine has two solid forms, <U+03B1>- and <U+03B2>-fluorine. The latter crystallizes at <U+2212>220&nbsp;<U+00B0>C (<U+2212>364&nbsp;<U+00B0>F) and is transparent and soft, with the same disordered [[Cubic crystal system|cubic]] structure of freshly crystallized solid oxygen,{{sfn|Dean|1999|p=523}}{{#tag:ref|<U+03B1>-Fluorine has a regular pattern of molecules and is a crystalline solid, but its molecules do not have a specific orientation. <U+03B2>-Fluorine's molecules have fixed location (reminiscent of the atom locations in the [[A15 phases]]) and minimal rotational uncertainty. For further detail on <U+03B1>-fluorine, see the 1970 structure by Pauling.<ref>{{harvnb|Pauling|Keaveny|Robinson|1970}}.</ref> For further detail on the concept of disorder in crystals, see the referenced general reviews.<ref>{{harvnb|B<U+00FC>rgi|2000}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|M<U+00FC>ller|2009}}.</ref>||group="note"}} unlike the [[orthorhombic crystal system|orthorhombic]] systems of other solid halogens.{{sfn|Young|1975|p=10}}<ref name="Barrett 1967"/> Further cooling to <U+2212>228&nbsp;<U+00B0>C (<U+2212>378&nbsp;<U+00B0>F) induces a [[phase transition]] into opaque and hard <U+03B1>-fluorine, which has a [[monoclinic crystal system|monoclinic]] structure with dense, angled layers of molecules. The transition from <U+03B2>- to <U+03B1>-fluorine is more [[exothermic]] than the condensation of fluorine, and can be violent.{{sfn|Young|1975|p=10}}<ref name="Barrett 1967">{{harvnb|Barrett|Meyer|Wasserman|1967}}.</ref>{{#tag:ref|A loud click is heard. Samples may shatter and sample windows blow out.||group="note"}}

===Isotopes===
{{Main|Isotopes of fluorine}}
Only one [[isotope]] of fluorine occurs naturally to any significant extent, the stable {{chem|19|F}} that has ten [[neutron]]s.<ref>{{Harvnb|National Nuclear Data Center|NuDat 2.1|loc=[http://www.nndc.bnl.gov/nudat2/reCenter.jsp?z=9&n=10 Fluorine-19]}}.</ref> It has a high [[magnetogyric ratio]]{{#tag:ref|The ratio of the angular momentum to magnetic moment is called the gyromagnetic ratio. "Certain nuclei can for many purposes be thought of as spinning round an axis like the Earth or like a top. In general the spin endows them with angular momentum and with a magnetic moment; the first because of their mass, the second because all or part of their electric charge may be rotating with the mass."<ref>{{harvnb|Vigoureux|1961}}.</ref>|group="note"}} and exceptional sensitivity to magnetic fields; because it is also [[monoisotopic element|the only stable isotope]], it is used in [[magnetic resonance imaging]].<ref>{{harvnb|Meusinger|Chippendale|Fairhurst|2012|pp=752, 754}}.</ref> Seventeen [[radioisotope]]s with [[mass number]]s from 14 to 31 have been synthesized, of which {{chem|18|F}} is the most stable with a [[half-life]] of 109.77&nbsp;minutes. Other radioisotopes have half-lives less than 70&nbsp;seconds; most decay in less than half a second.<ref name="isotopes">{{Harvnb|National Nuclear Data Center|NuDat 2.1}}.</ref> The isotopes {{chem|17|F}} and {{chem|18|F}} undergo [[positron emission|<U+03B2><sup>+</sup> decay]], lighter isotopes decay via [[electron capture]], and those heavier than {{chem|19|F}} undergo [[beta minus decay|<U+03B2><sup><U+2212></sup> decay]] or [[neutron emission]].<ref name="isotopes"/> One [[nuclear isomer|metastable isomer]] of fluorine is known, {{chem|18m|F}}, with a half-life of 234&nbsp;nanoseconds.<ref>{{harvnb|''NUBASE''|2003|p=29}}.</ref>

==Occurrence==
{{Main|Origin and occurrence of fluorine}}

===Universe===
