Other minerals such as [[topaz]] contain fluorine. Fluorides, unlike other halides, are insoluble and do not occur in commercially favorable concentrations in saline waters.{{sfn|Greenwood|Earnshaw|1998|p=795}} Trace quantities of organofluorines of uncertain origin have been detected in volcanic eruptions and geothermal springs.{{sfn|Gribble|2002}} The existence of gaseous fluorine in crystals, suggested by the smell of crushed [[antozonite]], is contentious;<ref>{{Harvnb|Richter|Hahn|Fuchs|2001|p=3}}.</ref><ref name="Elementar">{{Harvnb|Schmedt|Mangstl|Kraus|2012}}.</ref> a 2012 study reported the presence of 0.04% {{chem|F|2}} by weight in antozonite, attributing these [[inclusion (mineral)|inclusions]] to radiation from the presence of tiny amounts of [[uranium]].<ref name="Elementar"/>

==History==

{{Main|History of fluorine}}

===Early discoveries===
[[File:Book9-25.gif|thumb|right|upright|alt=Woodcut image showing man at open hearth with tongs and machine bellows to the side in background, man at water-operated hammer with quenching sluice nearby in foreground|upright|Steelmaking illustration from ''[[De re metallica]]'']]
In 1529, [[Georgius Agricola]] described fluorite as an additive used to lower the melting point of metals during [[smelting]].{{sfn|Greenwood|Earnshaw|1998|p=790}}<ref name="assassinated">{{harvnb|Senning|2007|p=[https://books.google.com/?id=Fl4sdCYrq3cC&pg=PA149 149]}}.</ref>{{#tag:ref|[[Basilius Valentinus]] supposedly described fluorite in the late 15th century, but because his writings were uncovered 200 years later, this work's veracity is doubtful.<ref name="PopSci">{{Harvnb|Stillman|1912}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Principe|2012|pp=140, 145}}.</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Agricola|Hoover|Hoover|1912|loc=footnotes and commentary, pp. xxx, 38, 409, 430, 461, 608}}.</ref>||group="note"}} He penned the Latin word ''fluor<U+00E9>s'' (''fluo,'' flow) for fluorite rocks. The name later evolved into ''fluorspar'' (still commonly used) and then ''fluorite''.<ref name="KGS fluorite terminology">{{harvnb|Norwood|Fohs|1907|p=[http://archive.org/stream/bulletin01kentgoog#page/n94/mode/2up 52]}}.</ref>{{sfn|Greenwood|Earnshaw|1998|p=109}}<ref>{{Harvnb|Agricola|Hoover|Hoover|1912|loc=preface, pp.&nbsp;[http://archive.org/stream/georgiusagricola00agririch#page/380/mode/2up 380<U+2013>381]}}.</ref> The composition of fluorite was later determined to be [[calcium difluoride]].<ref name="Weeks">{{harvnb|Weeks|1932}}.</ref>

[[Hydrofluoric acid]] was used in [[glass etching]] from 1720 onwards.{{#tag:ref|Or perhaps from as early as 1670 onwards; Partington<ref name=Partington>{{harvnb|Partington|1923}}.</ref> and Weeks<ref name="Weeks"/> give differing accounts.||group="note"}} [[Andreas Sigismund Marggraf]] first characterized it in 1764 when he heated fluorite with sulfuric acid, and the resulting solution corroded its glass container.<ref>{{harvnb|Marggraf|1770}}.</ref><ref name="ModFcchem"/> Swedish chemist [[Carl Wilhelm Scheele]] repeated the experiment in 1771, and named the acidic product ''fluss-spats-syran'' (fluorspar acid).<ref name="ModFcchem"/><ref>{{harvnb|Scheele|1771}}.</ref> In 1810, the French physicist [[Andr<U+00E9>-Marie Amp<U+00E8>re]] suggested that hydrogen and an element analogous to chlorine constituted hydrofluoric acid.<ref>{{harvnb|Amp<U+00E8>re|1816}}.</ref> [[Humphry Davy|Sir Humphry Davy]] proposed that this then-unknown substance be named ''fluorine'' from fluoric acid and the ''-ine'' suffix of other halogens. This word, with modifications, is used in most European languages; Greek, Russian, and some others (following Amp<U+00E8>re's suggestion) use the name ''ftor'' or derivatives, from the Greek <U+03C6><U+03B8><U+03CC><U+03C1><U+03B9><U+03BF><U+03C2> (''phthorios'', destructive) .{{sfn|Davy|1813|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=dhdGAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA278 278]}}{{sfn|Banks|1986|p=11}} The New Latin name ''fluorum'' gave the element its current symbol '''F'''; Fl was used in early papers.<ref name="dissolve"/>{{#tag:ref|Fl, since 2012, is used for [[flerovium]].||group="note"}}

===Isolation===
Initial studies on fluorine were so dangerous that several 19th century experimenters were deemed "fluorine martyrs" after misfortunes with hydrofluoric acid.{{#tag:ref|[[Humphry Davy|Davy]], [[Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac|Gay-Lussac]], [[Louis Jacques Th<U+00E9>nard|Th<U+00E9>nard]], and the Irish chemists Thomas and George Knox were injured. Belgian chemist [[Paulin Louyet]] and French chemist [[J<U+00E9>r<U+00F4>me Nickl<U+00E8>s]] died. Moissan also experienced serious hydrogen fluoride poisoning.<ref name="Weeks"/><ref name="Toon"/>||group="note"}} Isolation of elemental fluorine was hindered by the extreme corrosiveness of both it and hydrogen fluoride, as well as the lack of a simple and suitable [[electrolyte]].<ref name="Weeks"/><ref name = "Toon"/> [[Edmond Fr<U+00E9>my]] postulated that [[electrolysis]] of pure hydrofluoric acid to generate fluorine was feasible and devised a method to produce anhydrous samples from acidified [[potassium bifluoride]]; instead, he discovered that the resulting (dry) hydrogen floride [[insulator (electricity)|did not conduct]].<ref name="Weeks"/><ref name="Toon"/><ref name=Asimov>{{harvnb|Asimov|1966|p=162}}.</ref> Fr<U+00E9>my's former student [[Henri Moissan]] persevered, and after much trial and error found that a mixture of potassium bifluoride and dry hydrogen fluoride was a conductor, enabling electrolysis. To prevent rapid corrosion of the platinum in his [[electrochemical cell]]s, he cooled the reaction to extremely low temperatures in a special bath and forged cells from a more resistant mixture of platinum and [[iridium]], and used fluorite stoppers.<ref name="Toon"/>{{sfn|Greenwood|Earnshaw|1998|pp=789<U+2013>791}} In 1886, after 74 years of effort, Moissan isolated elemental fluorine.<ref name=Asimov/><ref name='qwen'>{{harvnb|Moissan|1886}}.</ref>

In 1906, two months before his death, Moissan received the [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]],<ref name="Chem Nobel laureates">{{harvnb|Viel|Goldwhite|1993|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=jEy67gEvIuMC&pg=PA35 35]}}.</ref> with the following citation:<ref name="Toon">{{harvnb|Toon|2011}}.</ref>
{{quote|1=[I]n recognition of the great services rendered by him in his investigation and isolation of the element fluorine&nbsp;... The whole world has admired the great experimental skill with which you have studied that savage beast among the elements.{{#tag:ref|Also honored was his invention of the [[electric arc furnace]].||group="note"}}}}

