===Later uses===
[[File:Uranium hexafluoride crystals sealed in an ampoule.jpg|right|An ampoule of [[uranium hexafluoride]] or ''hex''|thumb]]
The [[Frigidaire]] division of [[General Motors]] experimented with chlorofluorocarbon refrigerants in the late 1920s, and [[Kinetic Chemicals]] was formed as a joint venture between GM and [[DuPont]] in 1930 hoping to market Freon-12 ({{chem|link=dichlorodifluoromethane|CCl|2|F|2}}) as one such refrigerant. It replaced earlier and more toxic compounds, increased demand for kitchen refrigerators, and became profitable; by 1949 DuPont had bought out Kinetic and marketed several other [[Freon]] compounds.<ref name="ModFcchem"/><ref name="Jstg">{{harvnb|Okazoe|2009}}.</ref>{{sfn|Hounshell|Smith|1988|pp=156<U+2013>157}}<ref name="DD Freon history">{{Harvnb|DuPont|2013a}}.</ref> [[Polytetrafluoroethylene]] (Teflon) was serendipitously discovered in 1938 by [[Roy J. Plunkett]] while working on refrigerants at Kinetic, and its superlative chemical and thermal resistance lent it to accelerated commercialization and mass production by 1941.<ref name="ModFcchem"/><ref name="Jstg"/>{{sfn|Hounshell|Smith|1988|pp=156<U+2013>157}}

Elemental fluorine's large-scale synthesis began during World War II. Germany used high-temperature electrolysis to make tons of the planned incendiary chlorine trifluoride<ref>{{harvnb|Meyer|1977|p=111}}.</ref> and the [[Manhattan Project]] used huge quantities to produce [[uranium hexafluoride]] for uranium enrichment. Since {{chem|UF|6}} is as corrosive as fluorine, [[gaseous diffusion]] plants required special materials: nickel for membranes, fluoropolymers for seals, and liquid fluorocarbons as coolants and lubricants. This burgeoning nuclear industry later drove post-war fluorochemical development.<ref>{{harvnb|Kirsch|2004|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=cqnEZSTA6cUC&pg=PA61 60<U+2013>66]}}.</ref>

==Compounds==
{{main|Compounds of fluorine}}
Fluorine has a rich chemistry, encompassing organic and inorganic domains. It combines with metals and nonmetals, and most noble gases,<ref name="Riedel Kaupp 2009">{{harvnb|Riedel|Kaupp|2009}}.</ref><ref group="note" name="metal">[[File:Periodic table fluorine.svg|200px|alt=118 squares with numbers and letters in them, mostly colored gray and green, with a few numbers and words outside the boxes]] {{-}} In this article [[antimony]] is included among the nonmetals (colored green) even though its chemical properties are closer to metals (colored dark gray). Separate sections are dedicated to the [[#Noble gases|noble gases]] (light blue), [[#Hydrogen|hydrogen]] (purple), and [[#Organic compounds|carbon]] (yellow). [[period 7 element|Period 7]] [[p-block]] elements, colored light gray, have not been studied and are thus excluded.</ref> and usually assumes an [[oxidation state]] of <U+2212>1.{{#tag:ref|Fluorine in {{chem|F|2}} is defined to have oxidation state 0. The unstable species, {{chem|F|2|-}} and {{chem|F|3|-}} have intermediate oxidation states which decompose at around 40&nbsp;K;{{sfn|Wiberg|Wiberg|Holleman|2001|p=422}} {{chem|F|4|+}} and a few <!-- just a few -->related species are predicted to be stable.<ref>{{harvnb|Schl<U+00F6>der|Riedel|2012}}.</ref> Experimental evidence for the [[fluoronium]] ion, where fluorine has oxidation state +1, was reported in 2013.<ref>{{harvnb|Struble et al.|2013}}</ref>|group="note"}} Fluorine's high electron affinity results in a preference for [[ionic bonding]]; when it forms [[covalent bond]]s these are polar and almost always [[single bond|single]].<ref name="NF charge">{{harvnb|Harbison|2002}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Edwards|1994|p=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=TRMRDXHWX7EC&pg=PA515 515]}}.</ref><ref group="note">The metastable [[boron monofluoride|boron]] and [[nitrogen monofluoride]] have higher-order fluorine bonds, and some [[metal complex]]es use it as a [[bridging ligand]]. [[Hydrogen bonding]] is another possibility.</ref>

===Hydrogen===
{{Main|Hydrogen fluoride|hydrofluoric acid}}
[[File:Boiling-points Chalcogen-Halogen.svg|alt=Graph showing water and hydrogen fluoride breaking the trend of lower boiling points for lighter molecules|Boiling points of hydrogen halides and chalcogenides, showing the unusually high values for hydrogen fluoride and water|thumb|right]]
Hydrogen and fluorine combine to yield hydrogen fluoride, in which discrete molecules form clusters via hydrogen bonding. Hydrogen fluoride thus behaves more like [[water#Chemical and physical properties|water]] than [[hydrogen chloride]].<ref name="Pauling HF hydrogen bonds">{{harvnb|Pauling|1960|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=L-1K9HmKmUUC&pg=PA454 454<U+2013>464]}}.</ref><ref name="Atkins HF">{{harvnb|Atkins|Jones|2007|pp=184<U+2013>185}}.</ref><ref name="New Scientist HF">{{harvnb|Emsley|1981}}.</ref> It boils at a much higher temperature than heavier hydrogen halides and unlike them is fully [[miscible]] with water.{{sfn|Greenwood|Earnshaw|1998|pp=812<U+2013>816}} Hydrofluoric acid <U+2013> aqueous hydrogen fluoride <U+2013> is a [[weak acid]] unlike the other [[strong acid|strong]] hydrohalic acids,{{sfn|Wiberg|Wiberg|Holleman|2001|p=425}}{{#tag:ref|See also the explanation by Clark.<ref>{{Harvnb|Clark|2002}}.</ref>|group="note"}} but is corrosive enough to attack glass.<ref name="H+">{{harvnb|Chambers|Holliday|1975|pp=328<U+2013>329}}.</ref>

===Metals===
{{See also|Fluoride volatility}}
Alkali metals form ionic and highly soluble [[monofluoride]]s; these have the [[Cubic crystal system#Rock-salt structure|cubic arrangement of sodium chloride]] and analogous chlorides.<ref>{{harvnb|Katakuse et al.|1999|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=pjFTI5KgMFkC&pg=PA267 267]}}.</ref>{{sfn|Aigueperse et al.|2000|pp=420<U+2013>422}} Alkaline earth [[difluoride]]s possess strong ionic bonds but are insoluble<ref name="dissolve">{{harvnb|Storer|1864|pp=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KPyLb5f-p4EC&pg=PA278 278<U+2013>280]}}.</ref> save for [[beryllium difluoride]], which also exhibits some covalent character and has a [[silicon dioxide|quartz]]-like structure.<ref name="Beryllium chemistry">{{harvnb|Walsh|2009|pp=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3-GbhmSfyeYC&pg=PA99 99<U+2013>102], [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3-GbhmSfyeYC&pg=PA118 118<U+2013>119]}}.</ref> [[Rare earth element]]s and many other metals form mostly ionic [[trifluoride]]s.{{sfn|Emel<U+00E9>us|Sharpe|1983|pp=89<U+2013>97}}<ref name="Crystal chemistry of fluorides">{{harvnb|Babel|Tressaud|1985|pp=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SaWLysMGF3cC&pg=PA91 91<U+2013>96]}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Einstein et al.|1967}}.</ref>

Covalent bonding first comes to prominence in the [[tetrafluoride]]s: those of zirconium, hafnium<ref>{{harvnb|Brown et al.|2005|p=[https://books.google.com/?id=DvqwTdVhjMEC&pg=PA144 144]}}.</ref><ref name="Perry 2011 193">{{harvnb|Perry|2011|p=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SFD30BvPBhoC&pg=PA193 193]}}.</ref> and several actinides<ref>{{harvnb|Kern et al.|1994}}.</ref> are ionic with high melting points,{{sfn|Lide|2004|pp=4.60, 4.76, 4.92, 4.96}}{{#tag:ref|{{chem|Zr|F|4}} melts at 932&nbsp;<U+00B0>C (1710&nbsp;<U+00B0>F),{{sfn|Lide|2004|p=4.96}} {{chem|Hf|F|4}} sublimes at 968&nbsp;<U+00B0>C (1774&nbsp;<U+00B0>F),<ref name="Perry 2011 193"/> and {{chem|U|F|4}} melts at 1036&nbsp;<U+00B0>C (1897&nbsp;<U+00B0>F).{{sfn|Lide|2004|p=4.92}}|group="note"}} while those of titanium,{{sfn|Greenwood|Earnshaw|1998|p=964}} vanadium,<ref>{{harvnb|Becker|M<U+00FC>ller|1990}}.</ref> and niobium are polymeric,{{sfn|Greenwood|Earnshaw|1998|p=990}} melting or decomposing at no more than 350&nbsp;<U+00B0>C (660&nbsp;<U+00B0>F).{{sfn|Lide|2004|pp=4.72, 4.91, 4.93}} [[Pentafluoride]]s continue this trend with their linear polymers and [[oligomer]]ic complexes.{{sfn|Greenwood|Earnshaw|1998|pp=561<U+2013>563}}{{sfn|Emel<U+00E9>us|Sharpe|1983|pp=256<U+2013>277}}{{sfn|Mackay|Mackay|Henderson|2002|pp=355<U+2013>356}} Thirteen metal [[hexafluoride]]s are known,{{#tag:ref|These thirteen are those of molybdenum, technetium, ruthenium, rhodium, tungsten, rhenium, osmium, iridium, platinum, polonium, uranium, neptunium and plutonium.|group="note"}} all octahedral, and are mostly volatile solids but for liquid {{chem|link=molybdenum hexafluoride|Mo|F|6}} and {{chem|link=rhenium hexafluoride|Re|F|6}}, and gaseous {{chem|link=tungsten hexafluoride|W|F|6}}.{{sfn|Greenwood|Earnshaw|1998|loc=(various pages, by metal in respective chapters)}}{{sfn|Lide|2004|pp=4.71, 4.78, 4.92}}<ref name="D_BLOCK_XF6">{{harvnb|Drews et al.|2006}}.</ref> [[Rhenium heptafluoride]], the only characterized metal [[heptafluoride]], is a low-melting molecular solid with [[pentagonal bipyramidal molecular geometry]].{{sfn|Greenwood|Earnshaw|1998|p=819}} Metal fluorides with more fluorine atoms are particularly reactive.<ref>{{harvnb|Bartlett|1962}}.</ref>

