===Other reactive nonmetals===
[[File:Chlorine-trifluoride-3D-balls.png|thumb|[[Chlorine trifluoride]], whose corrosive potential ignites asbestos, concrete, sand and other fire retardants{{sfn|Air Products and Chemicals|2004|p=1}}]]
Binary fluorides of metalloids and p-block nonmetals are generally covalent and volatile, with varying reactivities. [[Period 3]] and heavier nonmetals can form [[hypervalent molecule|hypervalent]] fluorides.<ref name=Noury>{{harvnb|Noury|Silvi|Gillespie|2002}}.</ref>

[[Boron trifluoride]] is planar and possesses an incomplete octet. It functions as a [[Lewis acids and bases|Lewis acid]] and combines with Lewis bases like ammonia to form [[adduct]]s.<ref>{{harvnb|Chang|Goldsby|2013|p=706}}.</ref> [[Carbon tetrafluoride]] is tetrahedral and inert;{{#tag:ref|Carbon tetrafluoride is formally organic, but is included here rather than in the [[#Organic compounds|organofluorine chemistry section]] <U+2013> where more complex carbon-fluorine compounds are discussed <U+2013> for comparison with {{chem|Si|F|4}} and {{chem|Ge|F|4}}.|group="note"}} [[carbon group|its group]] analogues, silicon and germanium tetrafluoride, are also tetrahedral<ref>{{harvnb|Ellis|2001|p=69}}.</ref> but behave as Lewis acids.{{sfn|Aigueperse et al.|2000|p=423}}{{sfn|Wiberg|Wiberg|Holleman|2001|p=897}} The [[pnictogen]]s form trifluorides that increase in reactivity and basicity with higher molecular weight, although [[nitrogen trifluoride]] resists hydrolysis and is not basic.<ref name="PnFx">{{harvnb|Raghavan|1998|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=pBiS0jc-kWIC&pg=PA164 164<U+2013>165]}}.</ref> Phosphorus, arsenic, and antimony form pentafluorides more reactive than their respective trifluorides, with [[antimony pentafluoride]] the strongest neutral Lewis acid known.{{sfn|Greenwood|Earnshaw|1998|pp=561<U+2013>563}}<ref name=Arsenic>{{harvnb|Godfrey et al.|1998|p=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vVhpurkfeN4C&pg=PA98 98]}}.</ref>{{sfn|Aigueperse et al.|2000|p=432}}

[[Chalcogen]]s have diverse fluorides: unstable difluorides have been reported for oxygen (the only known compound with oxygen in an oxidation state of +2), sulfur, and selenium; tetrafluorides and hexafluorides exist for sulfur, selenium, and tellurium. The latter are stabilized by more fluorine atoms and lighter central atoms, so [[sulfur hexafluoride]] is especially inert.<ref name="(O,S,Se,Te)Fn">{{harvnb|Murthy|Mehdi Ali|Ashok|1995|pp=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0xl17YU8WzQC&pg=PA180 180<U+2013>182], [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0xl17YU8WzQC&pg=PA206 206<U+2013>208]}}.</ref>{{sfn|Greenwood|Earnshaw|1998|pp=638<U+2013>640, 683<U+2013>689, 767<U+2013>778}} Chlorine, bromine, and iodine can each form mono-, tri-, and pentafluorides, but only [[iodine heptafluoride]] has been characterized among possible [[interhalogen]] heptafluorides.{{sfn|Wiberg|Wiberg|Holleman|2001|pp=435<U+2013>436}} Many of them are powerful sources of fluorine atoms, and chlorine trifluoride's industrial applications require precautions similar to those applying to fluorine.{{sfn|Greenwood|Earnshaw|1998|pp=828<U+2013>830}}<ref name=Patnaik>{{harvnb|Patnaik|2007|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-CRRJBVv5d0C&pg=PA478 478<U+2013>479]}}.</ref>

===Noble gases===
{{main|Noble gas compound}}
[[File:Xenon tetrafluoride crop.gif|thumb|left|alt=Black-and-white photo showing transparent crystals in a dish|These xenon tetrafluoride crystals were photographed in 1962. Its synthesis, as with xenon hexafluoroplatinate, surprised many chemists.{{sfn|Moeller|Bailar|Kleinberg|1980|p=236}}]]
[[Noble gas]]es, having complete electron shells, defied reaction with other elements until 1962 when [[Neil Bartlett (chemist)|Neil Bartlett]] reported synthesis of [[xenon hexafluoroplatinate]];{{sfn|Wiberg|Wiberg|Holleman|2001|pp=392<U+2013>393}} [[xenon difluoride]], [[xenon tetrafluoride|tetrafluoride]], [[xenon hexafluoride|hexafluoride]], and multiple oxyfluorides have been isolated since then.{{sfn|Wiberg|Wiberg|Holleman|2001|p=395<U+2013>397, 400}} Among other noble gases, krypton forms a [[krypton difluoride|difluoride]],{{sfn|Lewars|2008|p=68}} and radon and fluorine generate a solid suspected to be [[radon difluoride]].<ref name=astatineradon>{{harvnb|Pitzer|1993|p=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CdUVspeIJAYC&pg=PA111 111]}}.</ref>{{sfn|Lewars|2008|p=67}} Binary fluorides of lighter noble gases are exceptionally unstable: argon and hydrogen fluoride combine under extreme conditions to give [[argon fluorohydride]].<ref name="Khriachtchev et al. 2000"/> Helium and neon have no long-lived fluorides,<ref name=HeNeCompounds>{{harvnb|Bihary|Chaban|Gerber|2002}}.</ref> and no neon fluoride has ever been observed;{{sfn|Lewars|2008|p=71}} helium fluorohydride has been detected for milliseconds at high pressures and low temperatures.<ref name="HeNeCompounds"/>

===Organic compounds===
{{main|Organofluorine chemistry}}
[[File:FluorocarbonCrabFish.JPG|thumb|alt=Beaker with two layers of liquid, goldfish and crab in top, coin sunk in the bottom|[[miscibility|Immiscible]] layers of colored water (top) and much denser perfluoroheptane (bottom) in a beaker; a goldfish and crab cannot penetrate the boundary. Quarters rest at the base.]]
[[File:Nafion2.svg|upright=1.0|thumb|alt=Skeletal chemical formula|Chemical structure of [[Nafion]], a fluoropolymer used in fuel cells and many other applications.{{sfn|Hoogers|2004|pp=4<U+2013>12}}]]
The [[carbon<U+2013>fluorine bond]] is [[organic chemistry]]'s strongest,<ref name=hagan>{{harvnb|O'Hagan|2008}}.</ref> and gives stability to organofluorines.{{sfn|Siegemund et al.|2005|p=444}} It is almost non-existent in nature, but is used in artificial compounds. Research in this area is usually driven by commercial applications;<ref>{{Harvnb|Sandford|2000|p=455}}.</ref> the compounds involved are diverse and reflect the complexity inherent in organic chemistry.<ref name="Jstg"/>

====Discrete molecules====
The substitution of hydrogen atoms in an [[alkane]] by progressively more fluorine atoms gradually alters several properties: melting and boiling points are lowered, density increases, solubility in hydrocarbons decreases and overall stability increases. Perfluorocarbons,{{#tag:ref|''Perfluorocarbon'' and ''fluorocarbon'' are [[IUPAC]] synonyms for molecules containing carbon and fluorine only, but in colloquial and commercial contexts the latter term may refer to any carbon- and fluorine-containing molecule, possibly with other elements.|group="note"}} in which all hydrogen atoms are substituted, are insoluble in most organic solvents, reacting at ambient conditions only with sodium in liquid ammonia.{{sfn|Siegemund et al.|2005|pp=451<U+2013>452}}

The term ''[[perfluorinated compound]]'' is used for what would otherwise be a perfluorocarbon if not for the presence of a [[functional group]],<ref>{{harvnb|Barbee|McCormack|Vartanian|2000|p=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=EdzO0aUxDJkC&pg=PA116 116]}}.</ref>{{#tag:ref|This terminology is imprecise, and ''perfluorinated substance'' is also used.<ref>{{harvnb|Posner et al.|2013|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=dthjVAGP-XIC&pg=PA187&dq=%22Perfluorinated+compounds,+hydrocarbons+that+are+fully+fluorinated+except+for+one+functional+group%22 187<U+2013>190]}}.</ref>|group="note"}} often a [[carboxylic acid]]. These compounds share many properties with perfluorocarbons such as stability and [[hydrophobicity]],<ref name="fluorotelomer"/> while the functional group augments their reactivity, enabling them to adhere to surfaces or act as [[surfactant]]s;<ref name=Salager2002>{{Harvnb|Salager|2002|p=45}}.</ref> [[Fluorosurfactant]]s, in particular,  can lower the [[surface tension]] of water more than their hydrocarbon-based analogues. [[Fluorotelomer]]s, which have some unfluorinated carbon atoms near the functional group, are also regarded as perfluorinated.<ref name="fluorotelomer">{{harvnb|Posner|2011|p=27}}.</ref>

====Polymers====
Polymers exhibit the same stability increases afforded by fluorine substitution (for hydrogen) in discrete molecules; their melting points generally increase too.{{sfn|Carlson|Scmiegel|2005|p=3}} [[Polytetrafluoroethylene]] (PTFE), the simplest fluoropolymer and perfluoro analogue of [[polyethylene]] with [[structural unit]] &ndash;{{chem|C|F|2}}&ndash;, demonstrates this change as expected, but its very high melting point makes it difficult to mold.{{sfn|Carlson|Scmiegel|2005|pp=3<U+2013>4}} Various PTFE derivatives are less temperature-tolerant but easier to mold: [[fluorinated ethylene propylene]] replaces some fluorine atoms with [[trifluoromethyl]] groups, [[perfluoroalkoxy alkane]]s do the same with [[methoxy|trifluoromethoxy]] groups,{{sfn|Carlson|Scmiegel|2005|pp=3<U+2013>4}} and [[Nafion]] contains perfluoroether side chains capped with [[sulfonic acid]] groups.<ref>{{harvnb|Rhoades|2008|p=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=k3AoGn0upf0C&pg=PA2 2]}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Okada et al.|1998}}.</ref> Other fluoropolymers retain some hydrogen atoms; [[polyvinylidene fluoride]] has half the fluorine atoms of PTFE and [[polyvinyl fluoride]] has a quarter, but both behave much like perfluorinated polymers.{{sfn|Carlson|Scmiegel|2005|p=4}}

==Production==

===Industrial===
[[File:Fluorine cell room.jpg|thumb|Industrial fluorine cells at [[City of Preston, Lancashire|Preston]]|alt=A machine room]]
Moissan's method is used to produce industrial quantities of fluorine, via the electrolysis of a potassium fluoride/hydrogen fluoride mixture: hydrogen and fluoride ions are reduced and oxidized at a steel container [[cathode]] and a carbon block [[anode]], under 8<U+2013>12&nbsp;volts, to generate hydrogen and fluorine gas respectively.<ref name="AcountF"/>{{sfn|Jaccaud et al.|2000|p=386}} Temperatures are elevated, KF<U+2022>2HF melting at {{convert|70|Celsius}} and being electrolyzed at {{convert|70|<U+2013>|130|Celsius}}. KF, which acts as catalyst, is essential since pure HF cannot be electrolyzed.<ref name="ModFcchem"/>{{sfn|Jaccaud et al.|2000|pp=384<U+2013>285}}{{sfn|Greenwood|Earnshaw|1998|pp=796<U+2013>797}} Fluorine can be stored in steel cylinders that have passivated interiors, at temperatures below {{convert|200|Celsius}}; otherwise nickel can be used.<ref name="ModFcchem"/>{{sfn|Jaccaud et al.|2000|pp=384<U+2013>385}} Regulator valves and pipework are made of nickel, the latter possibly using [[Monel]] instead.{{sfn|Jaccaud et al.|2000|pp=390<U+2013>391}} Frequent passivation, along with the strict exclusion of water and greases, must be undertaken. In the laboratory, glassware may carry fluorine gas under low pressure and anhydrous conditions;{{sfn|Jaccaud et al.|2000|pp=390<U+2013>391}} some sources instead recommend nickel-Monel-PTFE systems.<ref name="Shriver Inorganic">{{harvnb|Shriver|Atkins|2010|p=427}}.</ref>

===Chemical===
While preparing for a 1986 conference to celebrate the centennial of Moissan's achievement, [[Karl O. Christe]] reasoned that chemical fluorine generation should be feasible since some metal fluoride anions have no stable neutral counterparts; their acidification potentially triggers oxidation instead. He devised a method which evolves fluorine at high yield and atmospheric pressure:<ref name='year'>{{harvnb|Christe|1986}}.</ref>

:2&nbsp;KMnO<sub>4</sub> + 2&nbsp;KF + 10&nbsp;HF + 3&nbsp;H<sub>2</sub>O<sub>2</sub> <U+2192> 2&nbsp;K<sub>2</sub>MnF<sub>6</sub> + 8&nbsp;H<sub>2</sub>O + 3&nbsp;O<sub>2</sub><U+2191>
:2&nbsp;K<sub>2</sub>MnF<sub>6</sub> + 4&nbsp;SbF<sub>5</sub> <U+2192> 4&nbsp;KSbF<sub>6</sub> + 2&nbsp;MnF<sub>3</sub> + F<sub>2</sub><U+2191>

Christe later commented that the reactants "had been known for more than 100 years and even Moissan could have come up with this scheme."<ref>{{Harvnb|Christe Research Group|n.d.}}</ref> As late as 2008, some references still asserted that fluorine was too reactive for any chemical isolation.<ref>{{harvnb|Carey|2008|page=173}}.</ref>

==Industrial applications==
{{Main|Fluorochemical industry}}
Fluorite mining, which supplies most global fluorine, peaked in 1989 when 5.6 million [[metric ton]]s of ore were extracted. Chlorofluorocarbon restrictions lowered this to 3.6 million tons in 1994; production has since been increasing. Around 4.5 million tons of ore and revenue of [[United States dollar|US$]]550 million were generated in 2003; later reports estimated 2011 global fluorochemical sales at US$15 billion and predicted 2016<U+2013>18 production figures of 3.5 to 5.9 million tons, and revenue of at least US$20 billion.<ref name="ModFcchem">{{harvnb|Kirsch|2004|pp=3<U+2013>10}}.</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Miller|2003b}}.</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|PRWeb|2012}}.</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Bombourg|2012}}.</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|TMR|2013}}.</ref> [[Froth flotation]] separates mined fluorite into two main metallurgical grades of equal proportion: 60<U+2013>85% pure metspar is almost all used in iron smelting whereas 97%+ pure acidspar is mainly converted to the key industrial [[chemical intermediate|intermediate]] hydrogen fluoride.<ref name="AcountF"/><ref name="ModFcchem"/><ref name="SME mining 2006">{{harvnb|Fulton|Miller|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=zNicdkuulE4C&pg=PA471 471]}}.</ref>
