</imagemap></center>

[[File:SF6 current transformer TGFM-110 Russia.jpg|thumb|alt=Minaret-like electrical devices with wires around them, thicker at at the bottom|{{chem|SF|6}} transformers at a Russian railway]]
{{see also|Industrial gas}}
At least 17,000&nbsp;metric&nbsp;tons of fluorine are produced each year. It costs only US$5<U+2013>8 per kilogram as uranium or sulfur hexafluoride, but handling challenges multiply its price as an element, and most processes that use the latter in large amounts employ ''in situ'' generation under [[vertical integration]].{{sfn|Jaccaud et al.|2000|p=392}}

The largest application of fluorine, consuming up to 7,000&nbsp;metric&nbsp;tons annually, is in the preparation of {{chem|UF|6}} for the [[nuclear fuel cycle]]. Fluorine is used to fluorinate [[uranium tetrafluoride]], itself formed from uranium dioxide and hydrofluoric acid.{{sfn|Jaccaud et al.|2000|p=392}} Fluorine is monoisotopic, so any mass differences between {{chem|UF|6}} molecules are due to the presence of {{chem|235|U}} or {{chem|238|U}}, enabling uranium enrichment via diffusion or centrifuge.{{sfn|Jaccaud et al.|2000|p=382}}<ref name="AcountF"/> About 6,000&nbsp;metric&nbsp;tons per year go into producing the inert [[dielectric]] {{chem|SF|6}} for high-voltage transformers and circuit breakers, eliminating the need for hazardous [[polychlorinated biphenyl]]s associated with {{nowrap|oil-filled}} devices.{{sfn|Aigueperse et al.|2000|p=430}} Several fluorine compounds are used in electronics: rhenium and tungsten hexafluoride in [[chemical vapor deposition]], [[tetrafluoromethane]] in [[plasma etching]]{{sfn|Jaccaud et al.|2000|pp=391<U+2013>392}}<ref>{{harvnb|El-Kareh|1994|p=[https://books.google.com/?id=Wg1SnT6Cb0QC&pg=PA317 317]}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Arana et al.|2007}}.</ref> and nitrogen trifluoride in cleaning equipment.<ref name="AcountF"/> Fluorine is also used in the synthesis of organic fluorides, but its reactivity often necessitates conversion first to the gentler {{chem|Cl|F|3}}, {{chem|Br|F|3}}, or {{chem|I|F|5}}, which together allow calibrated fluorination. Fluorinated pharmaceuticals use [[sulfur tetrafluoride]] instead.<ref name="AcountF"/>

===Inorganic fluorides===
[[File:Hall-Heroult cell schematic.svg|thumb|Aluminium extraction depends critically on cryolite.]]
As with other iron alloys, around 3&nbsp;kg (6.5&nbsp;lb) metspar is added to each metric ton of steel; the fluoride ions lower its melting point and [[viscosity]].<ref name="AcountF"/><ref name="USGS">{{Harvnb|Miller|2003a}}.</ref> Alongside its role as an additive in materials like enamels and welding rod coats, most acidspar is reacted with sulfuric acid to form hydrofluoric acid, which is used in steel [[Pickling (metal)|pickling]], glass etching and [[cracking (chemistry)|alkane cracking]].<ref name="AcountF"/> One-third of HF goes into synthesizing [[sodium hexafluoroaluminate|cryolite]] and [[aluminium trifluoride]], both fluxes in the [[Hall<U+2013>H<U+00E9>roult process]] for aluminium extraction; replenishment is necessitated by their occasional reactions with the smelting apparatus. Each metric ton of aluminium requires about 23&nbsp;kg (51&nbsp;lb) of flux.<ref name="AcountF"/><ref>{{Harvnb|Energetics, Inc.|1997|pp=41, 50}}.</ref> Fluorosilicates consume the second largest portion, with [[sodium fluorosilicate]] used in water fluoridation and laundry effluent treatment, and as an intermediate en route to cryolite and silicon tetrafluoride.{{sfn|Aigueperse et al.|2000|p=428}} Other important inorganic fluorides include those of [[cobalt difluoride|cobalt]], [[nickel difluoride|nickel]], and [[ammonium fluoride|ammonium]].<ref name="AcountF"/>{{sfn|Aigueperse et al.|2000|pp=420<U+2013>422}}<ref>{{harvnb|Willey|2007|p=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=PrKemPXyXNIC&pg=PA113 113]}}.</ref>

===Organic fluorides===
Organofluorides consume over 20% of mined fluorite and over 40% of hydrofluoric acid, with [[#Refrigerant gases|refrigerant gases]] dominating and [[#Fluoropolymers|fluoropolymers]] increasing their market share.<ref name="AcountF"/><ref name="GIA f-chem report description">{{Harvnb|PRWeb|2010}}.</ref> [[#Surfactants|Surfactants]] are a minor application but generate over US$1 billion in annual revenue.<ref name="fluorosurfactant market">{{harvnb|Renner|2006}}.</ref> Due to the danger from direct hydrocarbon<U+2013>fluorine reactions above <U+2212>150&nbsp;<U+00B0>C (<U+2212>240&nbsp;<U+00B0>F), industrial fluorocarbon production is indirect, mostly through [[halogen exchange reaction]]s such as [[Swarts fluorination]], in which chlorocarbon chlorines are substituted for fluorines by hydrogen fluoride under catalysts. [[Electrochemical fluorination]] subjects hydrocarbons to electrolysis in hydrogen fluoride, and the [[Fowler process]] treats them with solid fluorine carriers like [[cobalt trifluoride]].<ref name="Jstg"/><ref>{{Harvnb|Green|Slinn|Simpson|Woytek|1994|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=TRMRDXHWX7EC&pg=PA91&lpg=PA91 91<U+2013>93]}}.</ref>

====Refrigerant gases====
{{See also|Refrigerant}}
Halogenated refrigerants, termed Freons in informal contexts,{{#tag:ref|This DuPont trademark is sometimes further misused for CFCs, HFCs, or HCFCs.||group="note"}} are identified by [[Refrigerant#Refrigerants by class and by R-number|R-numbers]] that denote the amount of fluorine, chlorine, carbon, and hydrogen present.<ref name="AcountF"/><ref>{{Harvnb|DuPont|2013b}}.</ref> [[Chlorofluorocarbons]] (CFCs) like [[trichlorofluoromethane|R-11]], [[dichlorodifluoromethane|R-12]], and [[1,2-dichlorotetrafluoroethane|R-114]] once dominated organofluorines, peaking in production in the 1980s. Used for air conditioning systems, propellants and solvents, their production was below one-tenth of this peak by the early 2000s, after widespread international prohibition.<ref name="AcountF"/> Hydrochlorofluorocarbons (HCFCs) and hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs) were designed as replacements; their synthesis consumes more than 90% of the fluorine in the organic industry. Important HCFCs include R-22, [[chlorodifluoromethane]], and [[1,1-Dichloro-1-fluoroethane|R-141b]]. The main HFC is [[1,1,1,2-Tetrafluoroethane|R-134a]]<ref name="AcountF"/> with [[2,3,3,3-Tetrafluoropropene|HFO-1234yf]] coming to prominence owing to its [[global warming potential]] of less than 1% that of HFC-134a.<ref name=HFO>{{harvnb|Walter|2014}}.</ref>

====Polymers====
[[File:A water droplet DWR-coated surface2 edit1.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Shiny spherical drop of water on blue cloth|Fluorosurfactant-treated fabrics are often [[hydrophobe|hydrophobic]].]]
{{Main|Fluoropolymer}}
About 180,000&nbsp;metric&nbsp;tons of fluoropolymers were produced in 2006 and 2007, generating over US$3.5&nbsp;billion revenue per year.<ref name="yearly FP production">{{harvnb|Buznik|2009}}.</ref> The global market was estimated at just under US$6 billion in 2011 and was predicted to grow by 6.5% per year up to 2016.<ref>{{Harvnb|PRWeb|2013}}.</ref> Fluoropolymers can only be formed by [[polymerization|polymerizing]] free radicals.{{sfn|Carlson|Scmiegel|2005|p=3}}

Polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE), sometimes called by its DuPont name Teflon,<ref name="encyc of structure"/> represents 60<U+2013>80% by mass of the world's fluoropolymer production.<ref name="yearly FP production"/> The largest application is in [[electrical insulation]] since PTFE is an excellent [[dielectric]]. It is also used in the chemical industry where corrosion resistance is needed, in coating pipes, tubing, and gaskets. Another major use is in PFTE-coated [[fabric structure|fiberglass cloth]] for stadium roofs. The major consumer application is for [[non-stick surface|non-stick cookware]].<ref name="encyc of structure">{{Harvnb|Martin|2007|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=xv420pEC2qMC&pg=PA189 187<U+2013>194]}}.</ref> Jerked PTFE film becomes expanded PTFE (ePTFE), a fine-pored [[synthetic membrane|membrane]] sometimes referred to by the brand name [[Gore-Tex]] and used for rainwear, [[personal protective equipment|protective apparel]], and [[filtration|filters]]; [[PTFE fiber|ePTFE fibers]] may be made into [[seal (mechanical)|seals]] and [[Dust collector|dust filters]].<ref name="encyc of structure"/> Other fluoropolymers, including [[fluorinated ethylene propylene]], mimic PTFE's properties and can substitute for it; they are more moldable, but also more costly and have lower thermal stability. Films from two different fluoropolymers replace glass in solar cells.<ref name="encyc of structure"/><ref name=DeBergalis>{{harvnb|DeBergalis|2004}}.</ref>

The chemically resistant (but expensive) fluorinated [[ionomer]]s are used as electrochemical cell membranes, of which the first and most prominent example is [[Nafion]]. Developed in the 1960s, it was initially deployed as fuel cell material in spacecraft and then replaced mercury-based [[chloralkali process]] cells. Recently, the fuel cell application has reemerged with efforts to install [[proton exchange membrane]] fuel cells into automobiles.<ref name="Fluorinated Ionomers">{{harvnb|Grot|2011|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=E8H1Hwd5GXUC&pg=PA6 1<U+2013>10]}}.</ref><ref name="Functional Materials">{{harvnb|Ramkumar|2012|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=ep7U5G4O3mQC&pg=PA567 567]}}.</ref><ref name="Chlor-alkali and chlorate technology">{{harvnb|Burney|1999|p=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rtm_bjQd8SUC&pg=PA111 111]}}.</ref> [[Fluoroelastomer]]s such as [[Viton]] are [[crosslink]]ed fluoropolymer mixtures mainly used in [[O-ring]]s;<ref name="encyc of structure"/> [[perfluorobutane]] (C<sub>4</sub>F<sub>10</sub>) is used as a fire-extinguishing agent.{{sfn|Slye|2012|p=10}}

====Surfactants====
{{Main|Fluorinated surfactant|Durable water repellent}}
Fluorosurfactants are small organofluorine molecules used for repelling water and stains. Although expensive (comparable to pharmaceuticals at US$200<U+2013>2000 per kilogram), they yielded over US$1 billion in annual revenues by 2006; [[Scotchgard]] alone generated over US$300 million in 2000.<ref name="fluorosurfactant market"/><ref name="Fluorinated surfactants">{{Harvnb|Kissa|2001|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=iAmE8v3bFnUC&pg=PA522 516<U+2013>551]}}.</ref><ref name="Ullman fibers">{{Harvnb|Ullmann|2008|pp=538, 543<U+2013>547}}.</ref> Fluorosurfactants are a minority in the overall surfactant market, most of which is taken up by much cheaper hydrocarbon-based products. Applications in [[surfactants in paint|paints]] are burdened by [[compounding]] costs; this use was valued at only US$100 million in 2006.<ref name="fluorosurfactant market"/>

====Agrichemicals====
About 30% of [[agrichemical]]s contain fluorine,<ref>{{Harvnb|ICIS|2006}}.</ref> most of them [[herbicide]]s and [[fungicide]]s with a few [[plant hormone|crop regulators]]. Fluorine substitution, usually of a single atom or at most a [[trifluoromethyl]] group, is a robust modification with effects analogous to fluorinated pharmaceuticals: increased biological stay time, membrane crossing, and altering of molecular recognition.<ref name=Theodoridis/> [[Trifluralin]] is a prominent example, with large-scale use in the U.S. as a weedkiller,<ref name=Theodoridis>{{harvnb|Theodoridis|2006}}.</ref><ref name="trifluralin">{{Harvnb|EPA|1996}}.</ref> but it is a suspected carcinogen and has been banned in many European countries.<ref>{{Harvnb|DG Environment|2007}}.</ref> [[Sodium monofluoroacetate]] (1080) is a mammalian poison in which two [[acetic acid]] hydrogens are replaced with fluorine and sodium; it disrupts cell metabolism by replacing acetate in the [[citric acid cycle]]. First synthesized in the late 19th century, it was recognized as an insecticide in the early 20th, and was later deployed in its current use. New Zealand, the largest consumer of 1080, uses it to protect [[kiwi]]s from the invasive Australian [[common brushtail possum]].<ref name="Beasley">{{Harvnb|Beasley|2002}}.</ref> Europe and the U.S. have banned 1080.<ref name = "Proudfoot"/><ref>{{Harvnb|Eisler|1995}}.</ref>{{#tag:ref|American sheep and cattle collars may use 1080 against predators like coyotes.||group="note"}}

==Medicinal applications==

===Dental care===
[[File:US Navy 090526-F-1333S-023 A service member embarked aboard the Military Sealift Command hospital ship USNS Comfort (T-AH 20) gives a Fluoride treatment to a patient during a Continuing Promise 2009 medical civil service projec.jpg|thumb|alt=Man holding plastic tray with brown material in it and sticking a small stick into a boy's open mouth|Topical fluoride treatment in Panama]]
{{Main|Fluoride therapy|Water fluoridation}}
Population studies from the mid-20th century onwards show [[topical medication|topical]] fluoride reduces [[dental caries]]. This was first attributed to the conversion of tooth enamel [[hydroxyapatite]] into the more durable fluorapatite, but studies on pre-fluoridated teeth refuted this hypothesis, and current theories involve fluoride aiding enamel growth in small caries.<ref name=Pizzo>{{harvnb|Pizzo|2007}}.</ref> After studies of children in areas where fluoride was naturally present in drinking water, controlled [[water supply|public water supply]] fluoridation to fight tooth decay<ref>{{Harvnb|CDC|2001}}.</ref> began in the 1940s and is now applied to water supplying 6 percent of the global population, including two-thirds of Americans.<ref name=Ripa>{{harvnb|Ripa|1993}}.</ref><ref name="Cheng Chalmers Sheldon 2007">{{harvnb|Cheng|Chalmers|Sheldon|2007}}.</ref> Reviews of the scholarly literature in 2000 and 2007 associated water fluoridation with a significant reduction of tooth decay in children.<ref name=NHMRC>{{harvnb|NHMRC|2007}}; see {{harvnb|Yeung|2008}} for a summary.</ref> Despite public endorsement, and the best available evidence showing no adverse effects other than mostly benign [[dental fluorosis]],<ref>{{harvnb|Marya|2011|p=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NKYy0w1OjJoC&pg=PA343 343]}}.</ref> [[water fluoridation controversy|opposition]] to water fluoridation on ethical and safety grounds<ref name="Cheng Chalmers Sheldon 2007"/> still exists.<ref>{{harvnb|Armfield|2007}}.</ref> The benefits of fluoridation have lessened, possibly due to other fluoride sources, but are still measurable in low-income groups.<ref name="Dental caries"/> [[Sodium monofluorophosphate]] and sometimes sodium or [[tin(II) fluoride]] are often found in fluoride [[toothpaste]]s, first introduced in the U.S. in 1955 and now ubiquitous in developed countries, alongside fluoridated mouthwashes, gels, foams, and varnishes.<ref name="Dental caries">{{harvnb|Baelum|Sheiham|Burt|2008|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=fZfXWhSmG1UC&pg=PA518 518]}}.</ref><ref name="Crest continuing ed">{{Harvnb|Cracher|2012|p=12}}.</ref>

===Pharmaceuticals===
[[File:Prozac pills.jpg|thumb|alt=Capsules with "Prozac" and "DISTA" visible|A 2008 [[meta-analysis]] of [[Fluoxetine]] (''pictured'') and three other antidepressants concluded that their efficacy, though statistically significant, was clinically insignificant "for any but the most severely depressed patients".<ref>{{harvnb|Kirsch et al.|2008}}.</ref>]]
Twenty percent of modern pharmaceuticals contain fluorine.<ref name="Emsley 2011 178">{{harvnb|Emsley|2011|p=178}}.</ref> One of these, the cholesterol-reducer [[Atorvastatin]] (Lipitor), made more revenue than any other drug until it became generic in 2011.<ref name="url_Crain's_2011">{{Harvnb|Johnson|2011}}.</ref> The combination asthma prescription [[Seretide]], a top-ten revenue drug in the mid-2000s, contains two active ingredients, one of which <U+2013> [[fluticasone]] <U+2013> is fluorinated.<ref name=Swinson/> Many drugs are fluorinated to delay inactivation and lengthen dosage periods because the carbon<U+2013>fluorine bond is very stable.<ref name="Hagmann">{{harvnb|Hagmann|2008}}.</ref> Fluorination also increases [[lipophilicity]] because the bond is more hydrophobic than the [[carbon<U+2013>hydrogen bond]], and this often helps in cell membrane penetration and hence [[bioavailability]].<ref name=Swinson>{{harvnb|Swinson|2005}}.</ref>

[[Tricyclic antidepressant|Tricyclics]] and other pre-1980s [[antidepressant]]s had several side effects due to their non-selective interference with [[neurotransmitter]]s other than the [[serotonin]] target; the fluorinated [[fluoxetine]] was selective and one of the first to avoid this problem. Many current antidepressants receive this same treatment, including the [[selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor|selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors:]] [[citalopram]], its isomer [[escitalopram]], and [[fluvoxamine]] and [[paroxetine]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Mitchell|2004|pp=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Duy5_XAD-vgC&pg=PA37 37<U+2013>39]}}.</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Preskorn|1996|loc=[http://www.preskorn.com/books/ssri_s2.html chap. 2]}}.</ref> [[Quinolones]] are artificial [[broad-spectrum antibiotic]]s that are often fluorinated to enhance their effects. These include [[ciprofloxacin]] and [[levofloxacin]].<ref>{{harvnb|Werner et al.|2011}}.</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Brody|2012}}.</ref><ref name="pmid17342653">{{harvnb|Nelson et al.|2007}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|King|Malone|Lilley|2000}}.</ref> Fluorine also finds use in steroids:<ref>{{harvnb|Parente|2001|p=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=fsfnKeFflUoC&pg=PA40 40]}}.</ref> [[fludrocortisone]] is a blood pressure-raising [[mineralocorticoid]], and [[triamcinolone]] and [[dexamethasone]] are strong [[glucocorticoid]]s.<ref name="dontburn">{{harvnb|Raj|Erdine|2012|p=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SQDge93GucMC&pg=PA58 58]}}.</ref> The majority of inhaled [[anesthetic]]s are heavily fluorinated; the prototype [[halothane]] is much more inert and potent than its contemporaries. Later compounds such as the fluorinated [[ether]]s [[sevoflurane]] and [[desflurane]] are better than halothane and are almost insoluble in blood, allowing faster waking times.<ref name="fut">{{harvnb|Filler|Saha|2009}}.</ref><ref name="anestetics">{{harvnb|B<U+00E9>gu<U+00E9>|Bonnet-Delpon|2008|pp=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QMVSvZ-R7I0C&pg=PA335 335<U+2013>336]}}.</ref>

===PET scanning===
{{main|Positron emission tomography}}
[[File:PET-MIPS-anim.gif|thumb|upright|A full-body {{chem|18|F}} PET scan|alt=Rotating transparent image of a human figure with targeted organs highlighted]]
Fluorine-18 is often found in [[radioactive tracer]]s for positron emission tomography, as its half-life of almost two hours is long enough to allow for its transport from production facilities to imaging centers.<ref name="18F">{{harvnb|Schmitz et al.|2000}}.</ref> The most common tracer is [[fluorodeoxyglucose]]<ref name="18F"/> which, after intravenous injection, is taken up by glucose-requiring tissues such as the brain and most malignant tumors;<ref>{{harvnb|Bustamante|Pedersen|1977}}.</ref> [[X-ray computed tomography|computer-assisted tomography]] can then be used for detailed imaging.<ref>{{harvnb|Alavi|Huang|2007|p=41}}.</ref>

===Oxygen carriers===
{{see also|Blood substitute|Liquid breathing}}
Liquid fluorocarbons can hold large volumes of oxygen or carbon dioxide, more so than blood, and have attracted attention for their possible uses in artificial blood and in liquid breathing.<ref name="Gabrielet">{{harvnb|Gabriel et al.|1996}}.</ref> Because fluorocarbons do not normally mix with water, they must be mixed into emulsions (small droplets of perfluorocarbon suspended in water) to be used as blood.<ref>{{Harvnb|Sarkar|2008}}.</ref><ref name="Schimmeyer">{{Harvnb|Schimmeyer|2002}}.</ref> One such product, [[Oxycyte]], has been through initial clinical trials.<ref>{{Harvnb|Davis|2006}}.</ref> These substances can aid endurance athletes and are banned from sports; one cyclist's near death in 1998 prompted an investigation into their abuse.<ref>{{Harvnb|Gains|1998}}.</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Taber|1999}}.</ref> Applications of pure perfluorocarbon liquid breathing (which uses pure perfluorocarbon liquid, not a water emulsion) include assisting burn victims and premature babies with deficient lungs. Partial and complete lung filling have been considered, though only the former has had any significant tests in humans.<ref name="ReferenceA">{{Harvnb|Shaffer|Wolfson|Clark|1992|p=102}}.</ref> An Alliance Pharmaceuticals effort reached clinical trials but was abandoned because the results were not better than normal therapies.<ref name="Alliance stock drop">{{harvnb|Kacmarek et al.|2006}}.</ref>

==Biological role==
{{Main|Biological aspects of fluorine}}
[[File:Gifblaar.jpg|thumb|The [[gifblaar]] is one of the few organofluorine-synthesizing organisms.]]
Fluorine is [[micronutrient|not essential]] for humans or other mammals; small amounts may be beneficial for bone strength, but this has not been definitively established. As there are many environmental sources of trace fluorine, the possibility of a [[fluorine deficiency]] could apply only to artificial diets.<ref name="gastroenterology1">{{harvnb|Nielsen|2009}}.</ref><ref name="quott">{{Harvnb|Olivares|Uauy|2004}}.</ref> Natural organofluorines have been found in microorganisms and plants{{sfn|Gribble|2002}} but not animals.<ref name="Murphy2003">{{harvnb|Murphy|Schaffrath|O'Hagan|2003}}</ref> The most common is [[sodium fluoroacetate|fluoroacetate]], which is used as a [[plant defense against herbivory|defense against herbivores]] by at least 40 plants in Africa, Australia and Brazil.<ref name="Proudfoot">{{harvnb|Proudfoot|Bradberry|Vale|2006}}.</ref> Other examples include terminally fluorinated [[fatty acid]]s, fluoroacetone, and 2-fluorocitrate.<ref name="Murphy2003"/> An enzyme that binds fluorine to carbon <U+2013> [[Adenosyl-fluoride synthase]] <U+2013> was discovered in bacteria in 2002.<ref>{{harvnb|O'Hagan et al.|2002}}.</ref>

==Toxicity==
{{main|Biological aspects of fluorine#Hazards|l1=Fluorine-related hazards}}
{{multiple image | align = left | footer = U.S. hazard signs for commercially transported fluorine<ref name="NOAA data sheet">[[#NOAASheet|National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]].</ref> | width = 60 | image1 = DOT hazmat class 6.1.svg | alt1 = A diagonal placard with warning poison | image2 = DOT hazmat class 5.1.svg | alt2 = A diagonal placard with warning corrosive | image3 = DOT hazmat class 8.svg | alt3 = A diagonal placard with warning inhalant | image4 = DOT hazmat class 2.3 (alt).svg | alt4 = A diagonal placard with warning oxidant }}
Elemental fluorine is highly toxic to living organisms. Its effects in humans start at concentrations lower than [[hydrogen cyanide]]'s 50 ppm<ref>{{harvnb|The National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health|1994a}}.</ref> and are similar to those of chlorine:<ref>{{harvnb|The National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health|1994b}}.</ref> significant irritation of the eyes and respiratory system as well as liver and kidney damage occur above 25 ppm. Eyes and noses are seriously damaged at 100 ppm,<ref>{{harvnb|Keplinger|Suissa|1968}}.</ref> and inhalation of 1,000 ppm fluorine will cause death in minutes,<ref>{{harvnb|Emsley|2011|p=179}}.</ref> compared to 270 ppm for hydrogen cyanide.<ref>{{harvnb|Biller|2007|p=939}}.</ref>
{{clear}}

===Hydrofluoric acid===

[[File:HF burned hands.jpg|thumb|alt=left and right hands, two views, burned index fingers|Hydrofluoric acid burns may not be evident for a day, after which calcium treatments are less effective.<ref name=Eaton>{{Harvnb|Eaton|1997}}.</ref>]]
{{See also|Chemical burn}}
Hydrofluoric acid is a contact poison with greater hazards than many strong acids like sulfuric acid even though it is weak: it remains neutral in aqueous solution and thus penetrates tissue faster, whether through inhalation, ingestion or the skin, and at least nine U.S. workers died in such accidents from 1984 to 1994. It reacts with calcium and magnesium in the blood leading to [[hypocalcemia]] and possible death through [[cardiac arrhythmia]].<ref name="OSHA">{{harvnb|Blodgett|Suruda|Crouch|2001}}.</ref> Insoluble calcium fluoride formation triggers strong pain<ref name=Goldfrank>{{Harvnb|Hoffman et al.|2007|p=1333}}.</ref> and burns larger than 160&nbsp;cm<sup>2</sup> (25&nbsp;in<sup>2</sup>) can cause serious systemic toxicity.<ref name="RMTHFE">{{Harvnb|HSM|2006}}.</ref>

Exposure may not be evident for eight hours for 50% HF, rising to 24 hours for lower concentrations, and a burn may initially be painless as hydrogen fluoride affects nerve function. If skin has been exposed to HF, damage can be reduced by rinsing it under a jet of water for 10<U+2013>15 minutes and removing contaminated clothing.<ref>{{harvnb|Fischman|2001|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=PyUSgdZUGr4C&pg=PA458 458<U+2013>459]}}.</ref> [[Calcium gluconate]] is often applied next, providing calcium ions to bind with fluoride; skin burns can be treated with 2.5% calcium gluconate gel or special rinsing solutions.<ref name="pmid2741315">{{harvnb|El Saadi et al.|1989}}.</ref><ref name="pmid17091088">{{harvnb|Roblin et al.|2006}}.</ref><ref name="pmid15461243">{{harvnb|Hult<U+00E9>n et al.|2004}}.</ref> Hydrofluoric acid absorption requires further medical treatment; calcium gluconate may be injected or administered intravenously. Using calcium chloride <U+2013> a common laboratory reagent <U+2013> in lieu of calcium gluconate is contraindicated, and may lead to severe complications. Excision or amputation of affected parts may be required.<ref name="RMTHFE"/><ref>{{Harvnb|Zorich|1991|pp=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sdB3KjhWzFQC&pg=PA183 182<U+2013>183]}}.</ref>

===Fluoride ion===

{{See also|Fluoride toxicity}}
Soluble fluorides are moderately toxic: 5<U+2013>10&nbsp;g sodium fluoride, or 32<U+2013>64&nbsp;mg fluoride ions per kilogram of body mass, represents a lethal dose for adults.<ref name="zzzzzzz23">{{Harvnb|Liteplo et al.|2002|p=100}}.</ref> One-fifth of the lethal dose can cause adverse health effects,<ref name="Nochimson"/> and chronic excess consumption may lead to [[skeletal fluorosis]], which affects millions in Asia and Africa.<ref name="Nochimson"/><ref name="pmid19305069">{{harvnb|Reddy|2009}}.</ref> Ingested fluoride forms hydrofluoric acid in the stomach which is easily absorbed by the intestines, where it crosses cell membranes, binds with calcium and interferes with various enzymes, before urinary [[excretion]]. Exposure limits are determined by urine testing of the body's ability to clear fluoride ions.<ref name="Nochimson">{{Harvnb|Shin|Silverberg|2013}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Baez|Baez|Marthaler|2000}}.</ref>

Historically, most cases of fluoride poisoning have been caused by accidental ingestion of insecticides containing inorganic fluorides.<ref name="Augenstein et al. 1991">{{Harvnb|Augenstein et al.|1991}}.</ref> Most current calls to poison control centers for possible fluoride poisoning come from the ingestion of fluoride-containing toothpaste.<ref name="Nochimson"/> Malfunctioning water fluoridation equipment is another cause: one incident in Alaska affected almost 300 people and killed one person.<ref name=Gessner94>{{harvnb|Gessner et al.|1994}}.</ref> Dangers from toothpaste are aggravated for small children, and the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] recommends supervising children below six brushing their teeth so that they do not swallow toothpaste.<ref>{{Harvnb|CDC|2013}}.</ref> One regional study examined a year of pre-teen fluoride poisoning reports totaling 87 cases, including one death from ingesting insecticide. Most had no symptoms, but about 30% had stomach pains.<ref name="Augenstein et al. 1991"/> A larger study across the U.S. showed similar findings: 80% of cases involved children under six, and there were few serious cases.<ref>{{Harvnb|Shulman|Wells|1997}}.</ref>

==Environmental concerns==

===Atmosphere===
[[File:Future ozone layer concentrations.gif|thumb|Animation|alt=Animation showing colored representation of ozone distribution by year above North America in 6 steps. It starts with a lot of ozone but by 2060 is all gone.|NASA projection of stratospheric ozone over North America without the Montreal Protocol<ref>{{Harvnb|Beck|Newman|Schindler|Perkins|2011}}.</ref>]]
{{See also|Ozone depletion|global warming}}
The [[Montreal Protocol]], signed in 1987, set strict regulations on chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) and [[bromofluorocarbon]]s due to their ozone damaging potential (ODP). The high stability which suited them to their original applications also meant that they were not decomposing until they reached higher altitudes, where liberated chlorine and bromine atoms attacked ozone molecules.<ref name="UNEP FAQ Ozone">{{Harvnb|Aucamp|Bj<U+00F6>rn|2010|pp=4<U+2013>6, 41, 46<U+2013>47}}.</ref> Even with the ban, and early indications of its efficiacy, predictions warned that several generations would pass before full recovery.<ref>{{harvnb|Crow|2011}}.</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Barry|Phillips|2006}}.</ref> With one-tenth the ODP of CFCs, hydrochlorofluorocarbons (HCFCs) are the current replacements,<ref name="EPA OLP Science">{{Harvnb|EPA|2013a}}.</ref> and are themselves scheduled for substitution by 2030<U+2013>2040 by hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs) with no chlorine and zero ODP.<ref name="HCFC0">{{Harvnb|EPA|2013b}}.</ref> In 2007 this date was brought forward to 2020 for developed countries;<ref name="HCFC Elim speedup">{{harvnb|McCoy|2007}}.</ref> the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] had already prohibited one HCFC's production and capped those of two others in 2003.<ref name="HCFC0"/> Fluorocarbon gases are generally [[greenhouse gas]]es with [[global-warming potential]]s (GWPs) of about 100 to 10,000; sulfur hexafluoride has a value of around 20,000.{{sfn|Forster et al.|2007|pp=212<U+2013>213}} An outlier is [[HFO-1234yf]] which has attracted global demand due to its GWP of 4 compared to 1,430 for the current refrigerant standard [[HFC-134a]].<ref name=HFO/>

===Biopersistence===
[[File:PFOS-3D-vdW.png|[[Perfluorooctanesulfonic acid]], a key [[Scotchgard]] component until 2000{{sfn|Schwarcz|2004|p=37}}|thumb]]
{{main|Biological aspects of fluorine#Biopersistence|l1=Biopersistence of fluorinated organics}}
Organofluorines exhibit biopersistence due to the strength of the carbon<U+2013>fluorine bond. [[Perfluoroalkyl acid]]s (PFAAs), which are sparingly water-soluble owing to their acidic functional groups, are noted [[persistent organic pollutant]]s;<ref>{{Harvnb|Giesy|Kannan|2002}}.</ref> [[perfluorooctanesulfonic acid]] (PFOS) and [[perfluorooctanoic acid]] (PFOA) are most often researched.<ref name="PFOA"/><ref name="PFOA evidence"/><ref>{{Harvnb|EPA|2012}}.</ref> PFAAs have been found in trace quantities worldwide from polar bears to humans, with PFOS and PFOA known to reside in breast milk and the blood of newborn babies. A 2013 review showed a slight correlation between groundwater and soil PFAA levels and human activity; there was no clear pattern of one chemical dominating, and higher amounts of PFOS were correlated to higher amounts of PFOA.<ref name="PFOA"/><ref name="PFOA evidence"/><ref>{{Harvnb|Zareitalabad|Siemens|Hamer|Amelung|2013}}.</ref> In the body, PFAAs bind to proteins such as [[serum albumin]]; they tend to concentrate within humans in the liver and blood before excretion through the kidneys. Dwell time in the body varies greatly by species, with half-lives of days in rodents, and years in humans.<ref name="PFOA">{{harvnb|Steenland|Fletcher|Savitz|2010}}.</ref><ref name="PFOA evidence">{{harvnb|Betts|2007}}.</ref><ref name="tox">{{harvnb|Lau et al.|2007}}.</ref> High doses of PFOS and PFOA cause cancer and death in newborn rodents but human studies have not established an effect at current exposure levels.<ref name="PFOA"/><ref name="PFOA evidence"/><ref name="tox"/> Other fluorochemicals also persist, like antibiotics and antidepressants in treated sewage,<ref name="fluorosewage">{{Harvnb|Lietz|Meyer|2006|pp=7<U+2013>8}}.</ref> and agrichemicals in farmland [[surface runoff|runoff]] and nearby rivers,<ref>{{harvnb|Ahrens|2011}}.</ref> since they do not biodegrade easily.<ref name="fluorosewage"/>

